<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-01-09T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-01-09T11:00:00-05:00" n="152" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d152">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/2760: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dearing</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-01-09T11:00:00-05:00">January 9, 1933—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 4:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>4. Department’s circular January 7, 3 p.m. Embassy’s telegram 3, January
                            4, 7 p.m. Peru’s position is that set out in circular. No replies yet
                            received from Argentina, Brazil and Chile. Believed at Foreign Office
                            changes going against Bolivia which would willingly accept any
                            suggestion promising cessation hostilities.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>